'''芝加哥唐人街'''，是位于[[芝加哥|芝加哥]]盔甲广场（Armour Square）社区的[[唐人街|唐人街]]，以舍麦路（Cermak Road）和永活街（Wentworth Avenue）为中心。根据[ftp://ftp2.census.gov/census_2000/datasets/demographic_profile/Illinois/2kh17.pdf 2000年人口普查] {{Wayback|url=ftp://ftp2.census.gov/census_2000/datasets/demographic_profile/Illinois/2kh17.pdf |date=20050122053912 }},拥有68,021名华人。在华人因迫害逃离加州之后，芝加哥成为美国第二古老的华人社区。

在芝加哥另有一处“新唐人街”，位于北区亚皆老街周围。

==教育==
[[芝加哥公立學校|芝加哥公立學校]]營運興氏學校<!--http://www.haines.cps.edu/images/haines_logo.png-->(John C. Haines School)和{{link-en|Phillips Academy High School|Phillips Academy High School}}。<ref>"[http://www.cps.edu/SiteCollectionDocuments/Zone%20maps/Elem_Near_North_West_Central.pdf Near North West Central Elementary Schools]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Ylxmjvg3?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20130517085518/http%3A//www.cps.edu/SiteCollectionDocuments/Zone%20maps/Elem_Near_North_West_Central.pdf |date=2015-05-24 }}." ''[[Chicago_Public_Schools|Chicago Public Schools]]''. Retrieved on April 7, 2009.</ref><ref>"[http://www.cps.edu/SiteCollectionDocuments/Zone%20maps/HS_West_Central_South.pdf West/Central/South High Schools]  {{webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5nWv6YiL0?url=http://www.cps.edu/SiteCollectionDocuments/Zone%20maps/HS_West_Central_South.pdf |date=2010-02-14 }}." ''[[Chicago_Public_Schools|Chicago Public Schools]]''. Retrieved on April 7, 2009.</ref>

興氏學校邊界包括唐人街和{{link-en|Harold L. Ickes Homes|Harold L. Ickes Homes}}(公營住宅)。2001年70%的學生是亞洲人和28%是黑人。<ref name=Ahmed-Ullahp1>{{cite news|author=Ahmed-Ullah, Noreen S.|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-07-01/news/0107010028_1_chinese-pupils-bilingual-program-black|title=School strives to expel racism|publisher=''[[Chicago_Tribune|Chicago Tribune]]''|date=2001-07-01|page=1|accessdate=2016-12-24|archive-date=2016-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225081349/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-07-01/news/0107010028_1_chinese-pupils-bilingual-program-black|dead-url=no}} "On one side live the children from the bleak Harold Ickes public housing complex, most of them black. On the other are Chinese-American children who generally live in cleaner, safer areas." - "With a student body that is 70 percent Asian and 28 percent black, Haines[...]"</ref> 
{{transH}}Connie Laureman of the ''[[Chicago_Tribune|Chicago Tribune]]'' stated that Haines, in 1990, was "crowded and dilapidated".<ref name=LauremanChanging1>{{cite news|author=Laureman, Connie|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-07-15/features/9002280145_1_chinese-immigrants-chinese-men-chinatown|title=Changing Chinatown|publisher=''[[Chicago_Tribune|Chicago Tribune]]''|date=1990-07-15|page=1|accessdate=2016-12-24|archive-date=2017-11-16|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171116185158/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1990-07-15/features/9002280145_1_chinese-immigrants-chinese-men-chinatown|dead-url=no}}</ref> Until Gandy Easton became principal in 1990, the school had [[de_facto_segregation|de facto racial segregation]] as ethnic Chinese students stayed in a bilingual program while black students took regular classes. Easton combined the two levels together, despite protests from ethnic Chinese parents.<ref name=Ahmed-Ullahp1/> By 2001 school authorities instituted programs to combat racism and ensure Chinese and black students socialized with one another.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ahmed-Ullah, Noreen S.|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-07-01/news/0107010028_1_chinese-pupils-bilingual-program-black/2|title=School strives to expel racism|publisher=''[[Chicago_Tribune|Chicago Tribune]]''|date=2001-07-01|page=2|accessdate=2016-12-24|archive-date=2016-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161225081344/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2001-07-01/news/0107010028_1_chinese-pupils-bilingual-program-black/2|dead-url=no}}</ref>

The [[Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_Chicago|Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Chicago]] supports the St. Therese Chinese Catholic School, a K-8 private Catholic school.<ref>"[http://www.sttheresechinatown.org/School_home.html St. Therese Chinese Catholic School] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090627054230/http://www.sttheresechinatown.org/School_home.html |date=2009-06-27 }}." ''St. Therese Chinese Catholic Mission''. Retrieved on April 17, 2009.</ref> {{Asof|1990}} almost all of the students were ethnic Chinese.<ref name=LauremanChanging1/>
